e Turks who infiltrated the Frankish camp at the Field of Blood (1119) disguised as bird sellers, to the Scottish camp followers descending on the field of Bannockburn (1314) waving laundry as banners to mimic a division of soldiers. This study also considers what contemporary society thought about deception on the battlefield: was it a legitimate way to fight? Was cunning considered an admirable quality in a warrior? Were the culturally and religious "other" thought to be more deceitful in war than Western Europeans? Through a detailed analysis of vocabulary and narrative devices, this book reveals a society with a profound moral ambivalence towards military deception, in which authors were able to celebrate a warrior's cunning while simultaneously condemning their enemies for similar acts of deceit. It also includes an appendix cataloguing over four hundred incidents of military deception as recorded in contemporary chronicle narratives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDeception (Military science)xHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMilitary history, Medieval. 4aMedieval History. 4aMilitary History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBannockburn.  aField of Blood.  aFrankish camp.  aScottish camp followers.  aTurks.  abattle of Hastings.  abattlefield.  achronicle narratives.  adeception.  amedieval warfare.  amilitary deception.  amoral ambivalence.  anarrative devices.  avocabulary.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311143099740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800104747?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800104747423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800104747/original  a978-3-11-143099-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles